---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import JwtDecoder from '../tools/JwtDecoder';
---
<Layout
  title="JWT Decoder & Inspector Online"
  description="Decode and inspect JWT tokens instantly. View header, payload, claims, and expiration without any server-side processing. Free online JWT debugger."
  keywords="jwt decoder, jwt debugger, decode jwt token, jwt inspector, json web token decoder, jwt parser online"
  faq={[
    { question: "What is a JWT token?", answer: "A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a compact, URL-safe way to represent claims between two parties. It consists of three Base64-encoded parts: header, payload, and signature, separated by dots." },
    { question: "Is it safe to paste my JWT here?", answer: "Yes. This tool runs entirely in your browser. No tokens are transmitted to any server. However, you should never share production tokens publicly." },
    { question: "Can this tool verify JWT signatures?", answer: "This tool decodes and displays the header and payload. Signature verification requires the signing key, which is not handled client-side for security reasons." },
    { question: "How do I check if a JWT is expired?", answer: "After decoding, look for the 'exp' (expiration) claim in the payload. This tool shows whether the token has expired based on the current time." }
  ]}
>
  <JwtDecoder client:load />
  <section class="seo-content">
    <h2>Free Online JWT Decoder</h2>
    <p>Paste any JSON Web Token to instantly decode and inspect its header and payload. See all claims, check expiration times, and debug authentication issues. No server-side processing — your tokens stay private.</p>
    <h3>What you can inspect</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Token header (algorithm, type)</li>
      <li>Payload claims (sub, iss, exp, iat, custom claims)</li>
      <li>Expiration status and time remaining</li>
      <li>Token structure validation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Layout>
